Steve Eder Steve Eder Last July, a 20-year-old community college graduate opened fire at Donald J. Trump during a campaign rally in Butler, Pa., killing an attendee. As the months passed, questions persisted about how this quiet young man had become a killer. So we investigated.→

Tawnell D. Hobbs Tawnell D. Hobbs In our reporting, we learned that Mr. Crooks’s mental health had been deteriorating. His father told investigators he would find him dancing at all hours of the night and talking to himself while waving his hands.

Steve Eder Steve Eder At the same time, Mr. Crooks appeared to be living a fairly normal life. He worked and attended classes, excelling as an engineering student with plans for a career in aerospace or robotics. People who know him said they had no idea about his troubles.

Tawnell D. Hobbs Tawnell D. Hobbs As we tried to understand Mr. Crooks’s downward path, we dug through government reports and public records about his academic life. In one essay we found, he argued for a voting method that would rank candidates by preference, saying the country needed a system that promoted kindness instead of division.

Steve Eder Steve Eder Our reporting also took us to western Pennsylvania, where we talked to people who knew Mr. Crooks. Many people still did not want to talk; they were shaken by the events of the previous summer. Others said they were still searching to understand what happened.

The Quiet Unraveling of the Man Who Almost Killed Trump
Thomas Crooks was a dean’s list student. As his mental health eroded, he stockpiled explosive materials before his attack on Donald Trump, our investigation found.
Right: Kristian Thacker for The New York Times

Last July, a 20-year-old community college graduate opened fire at Donald J. Trump during a campaign rally in Butler, Pa., killing an attendee. As the months passed, questions persisted about how this quiet young man had become a killer. So we investigated.→

In our reporting, we learned that Mr. Crooks’s mental health had been deteriorating. His father told investigators he would find him dancing at all hours of the night and talking to himself while waving his hands.

At the same time, Mr. Crooks appeared to be living a fairly normal life. He worked and attended classes, excelling as an engineering student with plans for a career in aerospace or robotics. People who know him said they had no idea about his troubles.

As we tried to understand Mr. Crooks’s downward path, we dug through government reports and public records about his academic life. In one essay we found, he argued for a voting method that would rank candidates by preference, saying the country needed a system that promoted kindness instead of division.

Our reporting also took us to western Pennsylvania, where we talked to people who knew Mr. Crooks. Many people still did not want to talk; they were shaken by the events of the previous summer. Others said they were still searching to understand what happened.
